    tag: 'AI',
    title: 'iter 287: Priority #2 (in-app Bittensor KB) — KB-STRUCTURAL SWEEP add spreadNaive (max/min) and spreadIQR (p90/p10) fields to priceRange6mo across all 44 non-root DOSSIER entries. First structural sweep since the SN53/SN107/SN93/SN118 iters compounded into three independent data points that the naive max/min spread is high-signal-but-spike-corruptible while the p90/p10 IQR spread is high-signal-and-spike-robust — encoding both alongside the raw distribution lets consumers of SUBNET_DOSSIER classify subnet cohort (tight competition-format vs open-marketplace) without recomputing from min/max/p10/p90 every time and without silently misclassifying spike-anomaly subnets. Motivation chain: iter 284 SN107 Minos surfaced a 6-day parabolic spike (2026-02-02 → 2026-02-08, 1.21 → 2.30 τ mean-reverted within ~10 days) that produced a naive 917× spread while the underlying post-spike range was ~2× — cohort classification currently depends on naive max/min and can silently misclassify subnets with brief historical anomalies; iter 285 SN93 Bitcast delivered the first dual-metric reading with the two metrics agreeing tight (1.73× naive, 1.47× IQR) and reinforced the competition-format cohort classification; iter 286 SN118 Ditto delivered the FIRST NEW ADD where naive AND IQR both indicated wide independently (9.64× / 6.24×) — three iters, three cohort archetypes (spike-corrupted / tight-agreement / wide-agreement) proved the IQR field is high-signal and not redundant. Sweep implementation: scripts/iter287-add-spread-fields.js reads lib/bittensor-kb.js, matches every `priceRange6mo: { min: X, p10: X, median: X, p90: X, max: X, samples: N, asOf: D }` single-line object via a strict-shape regex, computes spreadNaive = round(max/min, 2) and spreadIQR = round(p90/p10, 2) for each, and inserts the two new fields between max and samples preserving field order (min → p10 → median → p90 → max → spreadNaive → spreadIQR → samples → asOf). 44 replacements landed (all non-root DOSSIER entries; SN0 Root has no priceRange6mo by design — it is TAO itself, not an alpha token). Post-sweep width distribution using spreadIQR (spike-robust cohort classifier): 36 narrow (< 2×), 4 medium (2× - 4×), 4 wide (≥ 4×). Spot-verify samples: SN14 Cacheon spreadNaive 1.87 / spreadIQR 1.45 (competition-format, matches iter 281 reading), SN17 404—GEN 1.69 / 1.47 (competition-format, matches iter 280), SN53 EfficientFrontier 1.95 / 1.38 (competition-format, matches iter 283), SN93 Bitcast 1.73 / 1.47 (competition-format, matches iter 285), SN24 Quasar 5.77 / 3.62 (open-marketplace, IQR moderates naive), SN28 gm 5.56 / 4.04 (open-marketplace, IQR moderates), SN95 Actual 5.64 / 4.32 (open-marketplace, IQR moderates), SN118 Ditto 9.64 / 6.24 (open-marketplace, matches iter 286 dual reading), SN107 Minos 916.7 / 11.84 (SPIKE-CORRUPTED — naive misclassifies as extreme outlier, IQR crushes ~78× to a merely elevated 11.84× that still flags SN107 as high-dispersion but no longer as a data-corrupting singleton). The 36-narrow-vs-8-wide distribution across DOSSIER is a load-bearing structural finding on its own: MOST subnets exhibit tight IQR spread (< 2×), meaning the dominant miner-economics regime across Bittensor as measured is well-defined-scoring-⇒-narrow-dispersion, with only a minority of subnets (Ditto-style open agent OS, Quasar/gm/Actual/Ditto-style open-marketplace inference, SN107-style spike-anomaly subnets) in wide dispersion. Files touched: lib/bittensor-kb.js (44 priceRange6mo objects rewritten in-place; no other content mutated; module still passes require() smoke test), scripts/iter287-add-spread-fields.js (new sweep script — kept in-tree so future sweeps or field additions can iterate on the same pattern), lib/changelog-entries.js (this iter 287 entry). Iter 267 links:[] lesson enforced. DOSSIER count unchanged (45 total = SN0 Root + 44 non-root); priceRange6mo coverage unchanged (44/44); NEW field coverage introduced (spreadNaive: 44/44, spreadIQR: 44/44). Iter 288+ candidates: (a) continue NEW DOSSIER adds — next-highest non-DOSSIER by mcap via Taostats /api/dtao/pool/latest/v1 ranked list with SAME DOSSIER-membership grep guard pattern; (b) SN107-specific — add an explicit anomaly[] field to SN107 documenting the 2026-02-02 → 2026-02-08 spike so downstream consumers can gate on it programmatically; (c) enrich existing DOSSIER entries with abnormal[]/riskPattern fields where sparse (SN10 Sturdy, SN11 Dippy, SN13 Data Universe, SN18 Cortex.t candidates); (d) surface the 36/4/4 spreadIQR distribution in the §0 AI Insights system prompt so the model can reason about "typical Bittensor subnet is tight-dispersion" without recomputing from DOSSIER; (e) add cohort tag to DOSSIER entries themselves (cohort: "competition-format" | "open-marketplace" | "spike-anomaly") derived deterministically from spreadIQR bins, so downstream reasoning is cheaper.',
    body: 'Iter 287. Priority #2 KB structural sweep — added spreadNaive (max/min) and spreadIQR (p90/p10) fields to priceRange6mo across all 44 non-root DOSSIER entries. First structural sweep since iters 284/285/286 (SN107 spike disagreement + SN93 tight agreement + SN118 wide agreement) proved the p90/p10 IQR spread is high-signal-and-spike-robust while the naive max/min is high-signal-but-spike-corruptible. Encoding both alongside the raw distribution lets consumers of SUBNET_DOSSIER classify subnet cohort (tight competition-format vs open-marketplace) without recomputing every time and without silently misclassifying spike-anomaly subnets. Sweep implementation: scripts/iter287-add-spread-fields.js reads lib/bittensor-kb.js, matches every single-line priceRange6mo object via a strict-shape regex, computes spreadNaive = round(max/min, 2) and spreadIQR = round(p90/p10, 2), and inserts the two new fields between max and samples preserving field order (min → p10 → median → p90 → max → spreadNaive → spreadIQR → samples → asOf). 44 replacements landed (all non-root DOSSIER entries; SN0 Root has no priceRange6mo by design). Post-sweep width distribution using spreadIQR: 36 narrow (<2×), 4 medium (2×-4×), 4 wide (≥4×). Spot-verify samples: SN14 Cacheon 1.87/1.45, SN17 404—GEN 1.69/1.47, SN53 EfficientFrontier 1.95/1.38, SN93 Bitcast 1.73/1.47 (competition-format), SN24 Quasar 5.77/3.62, SN28 gm 5.56/4.04, SN95 Actual 5.64/4.32, SN118 Ditto 9.64/6.24 (open-marketplace), SN107 Minos 916.7/11.84 (spike-corrupted — naive misclassifies as singleton outlier, IQR crushes to merely-elevated 11.84×). Load-bearing structural finding: MOST DOSSIER subnets (36/44) exhibit tight IQR spread <2×, meaning the dominant miner-economics regime across Bittensor is well-defined-scoring-⇒-narrow-dispersion; only a minority (open agent-OS / open-marketplace inference / spike-anomaly subnets) sit in wide dispersion. Files touched: lib/bittensor-kb.js (44 priceRange6mo objects rewritten in-place; module still passes require() smoke test), scripts/iter287-add-spread-fields.js (new sweep script kept in-tree), lib/changelog-entries.js (this iter 287 entry). Iter 267 links:[] lesson enforced. DOSSIER count unchanged (45 total = root + 44 non-root); priceRange6mo coverage unchanged (44/44); NEW field coverage introduced (spreadNaive 44/44, spreadIQR 44/44). Iter 288+ candidates: (a) continue NEW DOSSIER adds — next-highest non-DOSSIER by mcap with SAME grep guard; (b) SN107-specific — add explicit anomaly[] field documenting the 2026-02-02→2026-02-08 spike so downstream consumers can gate programmatically; (c) enrich existing DOSSIER with abnormal[]/riskPattern fields; (d) surface 36/4/4 spreadIQR distribution in §0 AI Insights system prompt; (e) add cohort tag ("competition-format" | "open-marketplace" | "spike-anomaly") derived from spreadIQR bins to DOSSIER entries.',
