    body: 'Iter 196. PIVOT FROM PRIMARY: original iter 196 PRIMARY (per iter 195 verify-fire framing) was to self-sample emission_pct every Yuma tempo (~12min) into Vercel KV with a cron route, then read last-24h KV samples per held netuid into lib/report.js to project emissionPct24h and let the chip render dual values (`· N.NN% emit (epoch) · N.NN% emit (24h)`) + add a new emit-sustained-fair tier when 24h-mean ≥ 0.5% even if epoch=0. Research-first probe (per the SOP that worked iter 195): (a) GET /v2/teams/team_IsVRTrxCaZVhgTCa0QWuYnkk with VERCEL_AUTH_TOKEN returned `billing.plan = hobby`, `billing.status = active`. (b) Vercel Cron on Hobby is daily-only — Hobby tier permits 2 cron jobs but each may invoke at most once per day, so 12-minute sampling would need ~120 invocations/day = Pro plan required. (c) Vercel KV (Upstash Redis) is available on Hobby with a free tier (256MB / 30k commands/day), but without sub-daily cron the KV is useless: a daily-cron snapshot is no better than reading /api/subnet/latest/v1 inline at request time, since both are 1-of-20 daily epoch samples. CONCLUSION: PRIMARY is plan-blocked and parked pending a Pro upgrade or a non-Vercel scheduler (GitHub Actions cron is a viable free alternative — runs every 5min minimum, can POST to a Vercel API route that writes to Upstash directly; flag for future iter). PIVOT TO ALT: original ALT (c) "drawdown duration percentiles per iter 121 followup" was already shipped at iter 131 (verified via grep: ddDurationP50/P90/Max/underwaterRunCount computed in lib/report.js lines 826-867, returned in dd payload lines 933-936, rendered in §2 panel at Report.jsx lines 1225-1238 with tooltip explaining the distribution semantics). So the original ALT (c) is closed and the iter 195-fire framing was outdated. PIVOTED TO RELATED-AND-UNSHIPPED slice: render the drawdownVerdict TOKEN that those duration percentiles feed into. Same "data already computed, never rendered to the user" pattern as iter 193 emission chip — drawdownVerdict has shipped to §0 AI Insights since iter 121 (and to lib/bittensor-kb.js DRAWDOWN_VERDICT_HEURISTICS at iter 187) but never surfaced to a user-facing element. SHIP (3-file): (A) app/_components/Report.jsx line 453 destructure adds `drawdownVerdict: ddv` alongside the existing `drawdown: dd`; line ~1158 `.drawdown-head` h3 now carries an inline `<span className="dd-verdict-chip dd-verdict-{verdict-with-dashes}">` rendering `· verdict_label` (underscore→space prettyprint) with `title={ddv.verdictReason}` for the per-verdict threshold explanation. (B) app/globals.css adds `.dd-verdict-chip` base rule (color var(--dim), 11px tabular-nums, opacity 0.85, margin-left 2px) plus two opacity tiers — "resilient" verdicts (at_peak / resilient_absorb / recovered / within_typical_stretch / recent_noise) read quiet italic 0.7; "stressful" verdicts (flag_worthy / beyond_historical_tail / recent_deep_dip / shallow_but_extended / material_dip) read at muted 500-weight 0.95. NO green/red — §0 narrative owns severity, chip is information-only. (C) lib/changelog-entries.js — this entry. NON-CHANGES: lib/report.js unchanged (drawdownVerdict() function and payload key already shipped iter 121/123, no logic change); lib/ai-insights.js unchanged (§0 prompt already reads drawdownVerdict via existing channels); lib/bittensor-kb.js unchanged (DRAWDOWN_VERDICT_HEURISTICS already has read-rules for all 10 labels since iter 187); EMISSION_ALIGNMENT_VERDICT verdict tokens unchanged; iter 194 emit-off-epoch rename held; iter 195 §3 yield-table chip held. WHY THIS PIVOT IS THE SAME WIN AS PRIMARY: PRIMARY would have been a sustained-signal upgrade (the AI sees better data); this pivot is a surface-symmetry upgrade (the user sees the same data the AI sees). The vocabulary the AI uses in §0 to read drawdown state now appears verbatim on the user-facing §2 header — closes the same comprehension gap iter 193 closed for emission. PR #1 still OPEN, no Jai reply since 2026-05-28T07:55:09Z (~20 days, 1 comment). NO NUDGE.',
