    body:
      'Iter 160. Structural fix the last three iters (157/158/159) were dancing around. Setup: iter 159 eliminated the duplicate /api/account/history/v1 call (rolled back iter 158 chained Promise pattern, derived latestBalance from balanceSeries.at(-1)). Verify evidence (2026-06-16T12:09Z): Subnets 5EKFph3D…G5cd http:200/29.7s with pnlGroundTruth.available=true via paid tax/v1 AND profit/parity numbers matching the sheet — but verdict=None because balanceSeries len=0 (the single getBalanceHistory call still 429\'d, the catch returned [], no last row to derive latestBalance from, no currentPortfolio, no verdict). Mum_mantat 5HbWj5vb…jD1HL http:200/56.8s still tax_fetch_failed on /history/v1 → 429. Root 5Cnz1juP…SLbinH http:504/60.6s, was matched ✓ since iter 146 — first regression on a Root-tier wallet. Diagnosis: the SINGLE /history/v1 call still hits an exhausted bucket on cold-start or contention. iter 159 proved that even one call collapsed when /history/v1 429s, because the entire verdict path depends on currentPortfolio which depends on latestBalance which depends on balanceSeries succeeding. The retry-widening lever (iters 149/153/156) is at its budget ceiling (cumulative ~15.5s); pushing further past 20s puts every wallet at 60s timeout risk. The fix is structural: cache the successful result so subsequent throttled calls serve cached data instead of failing. Per lessons_taostats_account_endpoints.md, /api/account/history/v1 is already daily snapshots that lag 24h, so a 5min-stale cached series is functionally identical freshness to a fresh fetch. iter 146 proved this pattern works at /api/price/latest/v1 (lib/taostats.js:200-230); iter 160 mirrors it at /api/account/history/v1. Implementation: module-level Map `balanceHistoryCache` keyed by `${coldkey}_${days}`. Wrapper checks fresh window (60s) and returns immediately; on miss it calls the extracted `fetchBalanceHistory` helper (the previous getBalanceHistory body verbatim). On success it caches `{value, fetchedAt}` and returns. On any throw, if a cached entry exists within the 5min stale-OK window it returns the stale series with a warn log; only past the stale-OK window does it re-throw. Why 60s fresh + 5min stale-OK (same as iter 146 price cache): daily-snapshot data is high-cacheability, 60s is short enough that any push toward fresher data lands within one minute, and 5min stale-OK comfortably absorbs the worst-case throttle window observed empirically (iters 156-159). Why per-`${coldkey}_${days}` key: different callers pass different `days` values (buildReport uses 730, drawdown/vol math may use 365), and same coldkey at different windows is a different result set. Why a Map vs a plain object: cleaner cache-key semantics; the `_resetBalanceHistoryCache` test-only export uses `clear()` which is O(1). Test-only exports `_resetBalanceHistoryCache` + `_getBalanceHistoryCacheState` so smoke can assert cache hits/misses without reaching into module internals (mirrors iter 146 priceCache test exports). Smoke target: re-probe Subnets (IDEAL = matched verdict restored → tally 3→4 of 7), Mum_mantat (IDEAL = harvest_preferred restored → tally 3→4 of 7 OR 4→5 of 7 if both Subnets and Mum_mantat land), Root (IDEAL = matched ✓ restored OR at least no 504 timeout → tally 3→4 of 7 OR 4→5 of 7). On the FIRST cold-start fire, the cache is empty — if /history/v1 429s, behavior is identical to iter 159 (returns []). But the SECOND fire (within 5min) of any successful wallet will hit the cache and survive any throttle. So the smoke pattern is: fire 1 to populate, then fire 2 within 5min to verify cache-survives-429 path. Three scenarios per smoke: (a) IDEAL — fire 2 hits the cache (or fresh succeeds again) and the verdict lands; (b) STILL EMPTY CACHE — both fires 429\'d, the cache never populated, iter 161 candidate = pre-warm cache on /api/report cold-start via a setup phase; (c) CACHE STALE PAST 5min — fire 2 was past the stale-OK window, iter 161 candidate = widen stale-OK from 5min to 15min for /history/v1 (the lag tolerance is acceptable since daily snapshots). Trade-off honest: memory footprint is bounded (one Map entry per unique coldkey+days combo per cold-started Vercel instance; Jai\'s 7 pinned coldkeys × 1-2 day windows = ~14 entries max). Cache is per-instance not per-region, so Vercel\'s edge fanout means each cold instance starts empty — but the stale-OK window mitigates this once a single fresh fetch succeeds. No regression risk on the 5 already-verified wallets: cache miss path is identical to pre-iter-160 behavior (same fetchBalanceHistory call, same throw on failure). The cache only ADDS the survive-throttle path. PR #1 still OPEN, no Jai reply since 2026-05-28T07:55:09Z (~19 days).',
