    title: 'Light-endpoint timeout calibration fix — /api/price/latest/v1 bumped from 5s to 10s, /api/account/latest/v1 from 8s to 12s, /api/dtao/validator/yield/latest/v1 from 12s to 15s after the retroactive iter 142 verify caught that Vercel\'s egress IPs see substantially higher Taostats latency on these "lightweight" endpoints than the VPS baseline iter 144\'s numbers were calibrated against',
    body:
      'Iter 145. Direct fix-forward on iter 144\'s light-endpoint calibration. Iter 144 set /api/price/latest/v1 → 5s, /api/account/latest/v1 → 8s, /api/dtao/validator/yield/latest/v1 → 12s on the reasoning that "single record, <1s on a healthy Pro plan, fail-fast in 5–8s". That reasoning held against the VPS where iter 144 was smoke-tested. It did NOT hold against Vercel\'s egress, which the retroactive iter 142 verify on Jai\'s 7 pinned coldkeys exposed at 00:11Z today. After the 2026-06-15 multi-hour Taostats outage cleared (all three previously-stalling endpoints returned 200 in <1s from VPS at 00:10Z, healthy state), a sequential POST sweep of the 7 wallets through tao-wallet-report.vercel.app/api/report?skipCache=1 hit `Taostats /api/price/latest/v1 → timeout after 5000ms` on five consecutive wallets. A 65s wait + single-wallet retry reproduced the same 5.5s timeout cleanly. Meanwhile a direct VPS probe of the same Taostats endpoint at the same instant returned 200 in 0.22s × 3 samples. So the failure mode was NOT a transient throttle or a residual Taostats outage — it was a stable latency floor specifically affecting Vercel\'s egress IP range that the 5s cap was tighter than. Hypotheses for why Vercel sees higher latency on these endpoints than the VPS: (a) Taostats geo-routes Vercel\'s shared outbound IPs to a different region edge than direct VPS calls reach; (b) Taostats has a per-IP-range throttle bucket that\'s tighter for Vercel\'s wider, shared egress IPs (the existing code comment around the 429 retry calls this out for the free tier but iter 144\'s map didn\'t internalise it for the Standard plan); (c) post-outage degraded throughput specifically on Vercel\'s path. Whichever it is, the operational reality is the 5s cap is too tight. Iter 145 ships three timeout bumps: /api/price/latest/v1 5000 → 10000ms (2x), /api/account/latest/v1 8000 → 12000ms (50% more), /api/dtao/validator/yield/latest/v1 12000 → 15000ms (25% more). Heavy paginated endpoints (/api/account/history/v1, /api/transfer/v1, /api/delegation/v1, /api/accounting/tax/v1, /api/dtao/coldkey_alpha_shares/latest/v1) keep their iter 144 budgets unchanged — those numbers were derived from observed Pro-plan cold-cache behavior on healthy days, which matched both VPS and Vercel-side observation, so no calibration drift there. The bumped values are still well under the 60s Vercel maxDuration ceiling and well under the unmapped-path fallback (15s) for everything but yield/latest, which now matches the fallback. Trade-off: a stalled price endpoint now wastes 10s of fail-fast time instead of 5s — but iter 144\'s 5s was actively making the report unusable from Vercel on healthy days, so 10s is a net win. The 47–67% "failure latency improvement" framing iter 144 claimed in its commit message turns out to have been wrong (those numbers were measured against the iter 143 15s blanket on the VPS); the real iter 144 win was the directional separation of light vs heavy, not the absolute light-endpoint number. Iter 145 keeps the directional separation (light still has the smallest budgets) but moves to numbers that work in both environments. Diagnostic side-effect: when the retroactive iter 142 verify re-runs on iter 145\'s deploy, every wallet that completes is fresh evidence that the iter 142 sheet-parity classifier works as advertised on live data — the whole point of priority A from Jai\'s redirect. Pre-commit smoke 13/13 PASS (same test cases as iter 144, expected values updated for the three bumped paths). Iter 146 candidates: (a) FINISH the retroactive iter 142 verify on all 7 coldkeys now that the timeouts fit Vercel reality (this is the queued priority A unblocked by iter 145); (b) "Taostats degraded" §0 banner — iter 144\'s detection signal is still useful, but iter 145\'s wider light budgets mean the banner needs to be smarter about distinguishing "Taostats slow" from "Taostats down" (a 10s price/latest timeout on iter 145 IS suggestive of outage; on iter 144 it would have been ambiguous); (c) iter 142 parity verdict chip in §2 PnL UI block; (d) per-section timeout budget tracking ("price fetched in 5.2s / 10s budget") in a diagnostic panel. KB layer-stack unchanged (FIFTEEN — calibration fix, not a new verdict axis). PR #1 still OPEN, no Jai reply since 2026-05-28T07:55:09Z (~19 days).',
