    body:
      'Iter 136. Closes the iter 135 verify gap — the live LLM-failure path on Jai\'s primary 5Cnz1juP… coldkey rendered the §0 error card heading + body but NOT the verdict list, exposing that the iter 135 verdictFallback wiring was load-bearing at the component layer but not at the server layer: buildVerdictFallback() was only invoked from inside buildInsights() (always returned, always carried to the response on the happy + soft-fail-by-null-text paths), but the route had no try/catch wrapping the buildInsights call, so any unhandled exception in buildInsights — a chat() provider exception not caught by lib/llm.js (e.g. a JSON parse failure on Pollinations returning malformed body), a validateSections() crash on text the model emitted in an unexpected shape, a patchMissingSections() throw on a regex edge — propagated through to Next.js, which returned HTTP 500 with an HTML error page and no JSON. Client receives the 500, r.json() rejects on the HTML body, the fetch().then.catch path fires, state goes to { status:\'error\' } with NO verdictFallback set. Error card renders the iter 134 heading + body but the iter 135 list block is gated on state.verdictFallback?.length > 0 so it silently doesn\'t render. The iter 135 verify caught this via DOM read after the Playwright monkey-patch confirmed the COMPONENT renders the list verbatim when given a synthetic payload — meaning the missing piece was upstream of the component. Fix is two edits to app/api/insights/route.js: (1) import buildVerdictFallback alongside buildInsights from lib/ai-insights.js; (2) wrap `await buildInsights(report, { force })` in a try/catch — on success unchanged, on throw return NextResponse.json({ available:false, error:`Insights build failed: ${msg}`, verdictFallback: buildVerdictFallback(report) }, { status:200 }). HTTP 200 (not 500) is deliberate so the client\'s .then(({ok, j}) => …) branch runs and reads j.verdictFallback into state instead of the .catch path that bypasses it. Also enriches the 502 getOrBuildReport catch branch with `verdictFallback: []` — there\'s no report so the array is empty, but the explicit empty array keeps the response shape consistent across error modes so the client\'s `Array.isArray(j.verdictFallback) ? j.verdictFallback : []` defensive line behaves uniformly (not defensive-against-undefined sometimes and defensive-against-array-pattern other times). One narrow gap remains: if Vercel kills the function at the 60s maxDuration ceiling (Pollinations reasoning tier occasionally exceeds 60s on long prompts with retry — observed first-hand on iter 133), the runtime aborts before either route catch can fire and Vercel returns a 504 with HTML body — client still hits .catch with no fallback. Fixing that structurally requires embedding verdictFallback in the SSR page payload so the client component can render the fallback even when /api/insights never responds (natural iter 137 candidate, splits cleanly from this server-side hardening). Smoke-tested 3 cases in isolation pre-commit (1/3 buildInsights throw → catch path produces 3-row verdictFallback from a 3-verdict report; 2/3 getOrBuildReport throw → verdictFallback:[] with isArray=true; 3/3 empty report → verdictFallback:[] without throwing) — all PASS. The pre-existing iter 135 buildVerdictFallback() helper and lib/ai-insights.js buildInsights() happy/soft-fail paths are untouched — this iter only hardens the route layer. Behaviour change on the happy path is zero (the new try wraps the existing await unchanged). On the load-bearing error path the user now sees the §0 heading (iter 134), the muted body (iter 134), AND the six-row verdict tree (iter 135) when the LLM provider explodes mid-stream, not just two of the three. Non-blocking: paid PnL flow untouched, free-PnL preview branch + draft PR #1 still held pending Jai\'s 1/2/3 signoff (last updated_at 2026-05-28T07:55:09Z, ~24.5hr hold by 08:00Z). KB layer-stack stays TWELVE deep; this is the second resilience-layer iter (iter 134 stopped the silent vanish, iter 135 surfaced the verdicts to the component layer, iter 136 closes the server-layer load-bearing gap). Natural iter 137 candidates: (a) Priority 3 multi-window net-flow comparison (the deepest depth-debt now that the §0 error surface is structurally complete end-to-end through three layers); (b) embed verdictFallback in the SSR page payload so the client can render the fallback even on the Vercel maxDuration timeout case (covers the one remaining narrow gap above); (c) §3 quartet portfolio roll-up (alpha-weighted 1h × 1d × 7d × 30d quartet beside the existing 1d-delta block).',
